%md # Preparing Datasets for Analysis

Before we begin working with our CDRs we need to prepare our tower datasets and the relevant shapefiles. All analysis we carry out on our CDRs will have at a given geographic resolution/scale. In this case we are limited to administrative levels in Sierra Leone. For the purposes of this training, we will be working at the `District` level. Below we are given a tower dataset and we want to ensure that not only is the tower dataset good for our analysis, but that it has the proper geospatial information we need for analysis. Below we will be doing the following:

1. Review our tower data set to understand its structure. Perform and document any necessary cleaning and transformations. 
2. Review our district shapefile 
3. Perform a Spatial join on the cleaned tower dataset and district shapefile to get tower data with locality information
5. Export our new dataset to a file we will use in our data processing

%python
import geopandas as gd
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from shapely.geometry import Point

%python
import boto3
import io
s3 = boto3.client('s3')
obj = s3.get_object(Bucket='sierra-leone-lake', Key=path_to_tower_dataset)
towers = pd.read_csv(io.BytesIO(obj['Body'].read()))

#Since the longitude and latitude coordinate are unique to the site, we just care about the unique sites rather than cells.
towers = towers.drop_duplicates(subset=["site_id"], keep="first")\
    .reset_index(drop=True)

# In exploring the towers file, we see that there are some issues with this records. So we remove it from further analysis.
towers = towers[towers.site_id != "WELLINGTON"]

%python
# After the pre-processing, we can now tranform our towers files into a GeoDataFrame. This is like a dataframe that we can use to perform geospatial calculations. 
towers_gdf = gd.GeoDataFrame(towers[["Name", "site_id"]],
                      crs={"init":'epsg:4326'},
                      geometry = [Point(xy) for xy in zip(towers.longitude, towers.Latitude)])

%md 
> **What is a Spatial Join?** A Spatial join is a GIS operation that affixes data from one feature layer’s attribute table to another from a spatial perspective. Spatial joins begin by selecting a target feature and comparing it spatially to other feature layers. The target features will inherit the attributes from the other features if and only if the two features share the same spatial reference.

source: [www.wiki.gis.com](http://wiki.gis.com/wiki/index.php/Spatial_Join#:~:text=A%20Spatial%20join%20is%20a,spatially%20to%20other%20feature%20layers.)

%python
# Geopandas has a builtin method that allows us to perform spatial joins. 
towers_with_district = gd.sjoin(towers_gdf, locality, how="inner", op="intersects")\
        .rename({"New_Dist": "locality"}, axis=1)

%python
# We can also quickly plot our new GeoDataframe and explore the result.
base = locality.plot(color="lightgrey", edgecolor='black')
towers_with_district.plot(ax=base, marker='o', color='green', markersize=5)

%python
df_buffer = io.StringIO()
towers_with_district.to_csv(df_buffer)

s3_resource = boto3.resource('s3')
s3_resource.Object('sierra-leone-lake', 'training/data/towers/towers.csv').put(Body=df_buffer.getvalue())
